04270nam a22005055i 9780773564305DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19931993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735643057 a10.1515/97807735643052doi  a(DE-B1597)656054  a(OCoLC)1394871936  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1034.3.K54bM38 1993eb 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a971.064/0921 aMcDougall, John N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics and Economics of Eric Kierans :bA Man for All Canadas /cJohn N. McDougall. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Many Canadas of Eric Kierans -- tThe Quiet Revolution -- tProfessor and Polemicist -- tLévesque and Kierans, Ltée -- t“Cooperative” Federalism and the Break with Lévesque -- tThe Kierans Affair and After -- tThe Centre Cannot Hold -- tTax Reform and the Post Office -- tTelesat and the National Interest -- tFrom Minister to Critic -- tThe Unretiring Voice -- tWhose Resources Are They, Anyhow? -- tGlobalism, State, and Community -- tA Political Economy for All Canadas -- tKierans to Walter Gordon, June 1963 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMcDougall believes that study of Kierans' career is important for two reasons: Kierans not only combined practical business and governmental experience with a coherent economic and philosophical outlook but also maintained a comprehensive and integrated approach to the major issues in Canadian politics national unity, economic independence, federal-provincial relations, regional development, resource policy, and macro-economic policy. McDougall examines Kierans' career from his appointment as president of the Montreal Stock Exchange in 1960 to his service as chairman of the Nova Scotia commission on the Charlottetown Accord during the early 1990s. He focuses on Kierans' relationship with René Lévesque in the government of Jean Lesage, his fights within the Trudeau cabinet over the reform of the post office and the development of the Anik satellite, and his criticisms of Canadian economic and resource policies in the 1970s. Using Kierans' ministerial and personal records, his publications and speeches, interviews with him and his former associates, and a variety of secondary sources, the author argues that much of what Kierans said and accomplished is unique and remains relevant to the economic and political problems of today. Kierans has demonstrated that powerful political forces often prevent good ideas and determined effort from improving public policy but he has also shown that thoughtful and responsible public service can at least raise the level of public debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356430540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564305423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564305/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles